comments[2]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-07-19T15:37:46.603Z",maintainer-agent,"Evidence: PmClient.create/update/close now take contract-derived typed option bags (PmCreateActionOptions/PmUpdateActionOptions/PmClientCloseActionOptions) built by OptionsFromContracts over const-asserted *_SOURCE tuples in tool-option-contracts.ts — same objects that build the runtime tables, pinned by a parity spec; CLOSE_ACTION_OPTION_KEYS single-sources the close schema + close type. Typo/wrong-shape rejection enforced by tests/types/typed-action-inputs.test-d.ts via tsconfig.typetests.json wired into pnpm typecheck (CI gate). ListProjectedItem gains typed ListProjectedItemCore (row.id string|undefined, never unknown). No runtime behavior change; PmClient.run stays the wide escape hatch; custom schema fields keep the repeatable field option. Remainder honestly out of scope here: claim/release/copy/delete/restore convenience bags are still Record-based."
  "2026-07-19T16:09:04.938Z",codex-wide-sdk-20260719,"Final implementation correction: PmCreateActionOptions, PmUpdateActionOptions, and PmCloseActionOptions now derive from the executable CLI command option interfaces after stripping index signatures and internal runtime/policy keys, rather than deriving client options from MCP tool aliases. PmClient methods and the top-level create/update/close SDK helpers all consume these strict types. Compile-time tests reject typos, wrong scalar kinds such as priority=true, MCP-only aliases such as estimate, object/array values, and unsupported keys while accepting real client keys such as estimatedMinutes and file. pnpm typecheck and the full coverage suite pass."
learnings[2]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-07-19T15:38:36.272Z",maintainer-agent,"Deriving compile-time types from runtime contract tables requires const-asserted sources; widened annotations (X[] = [...]) erase literals permanently. Pattern: const SOURCE = [...] as const satisfies readonly T[]; export runtime clones + typeof SOURCE types, and pin them together with a runtime parity spec. Interfaces in composed option bags break implicit index-signature assignability to Record-based dispatch layers — use object type literals."
  "2026-07-19T16:09:05.803Z",codex-wide-sdk-20260719,"Public SDK client option types must derive from the executable command option interfaces, not transport-specific MCP aliases; otherwise accepted keys drift from runtime behavior even when a schema-derived type looks strict. Strip index signatures before projecting public mutation inputs so excess-property checks remain effective."
